scopecontent.p:
Frederic to mother. ALS, Columbian Hospital, Washington, DC. Stressing how
                        much he would like a picture of his mother to complete his family gallery;
                        speaking about friendship. 4 pp.

TLS from Harding. Acknowledging receipt of a report from the Second
                           Annual Convention of the Disabled American Veterans of the World War;
                           encouraging and thanking Forbes for his difficult work. 1 p.

TLS, marked "Personal" in pencil. Expressing frustration with reactionary
                           forces in the middle west who are hurting the cause of American farmers;
                           desiring moderation. 1 p.

ALS (RC), Monticello. Responding to a printed speech of Plumer's;
                           discussing the inviolability of institutions and the want of economy in
                           the English government. 1 p.

Confederate soldier. ALS, Charleston, S.C. To Colonel James Chesnut. Giving a
                  lengthy critique of remarks by Chestnut concerning the battle at Bull Run;
                  offering his own description of the events. 4 pp.

LS, Upperville. Reporting that the enemy is concentrating in Centreville;
                           Generals Stuart and Ewell have captured men and supplies; and General
                           Milroy has escaped to Harpers Ferry with small losses. 2 pp.

LS. Concerning the fact that the Conscript Law allows men to enlist in
                           local companies and thereby avoid the "principle theatre of hostilities";
                           asking that the law be changed. 3 pp.

ALS. Regarding the amount of corn available before the next crop;
                           expressing anger at the destruction of railroad lines beyond Greensboro
                           by "incendiaries." 1 p.

ALS, Petersburg. Giving his account of the enemy's explosion of a mine;
                           asking for advice about appointing new commanders in the wake of the
                           illness and injury of others. 4 pp.

Autograph memorandum of "Sundries for Mr. William Read to bring from Canton
                        for Mrs. James Read," including blue & white China dishes, butter boats,
                        and a tea caddy. 1 p.

ALS, University of Virginia. To the president of "Alabama Univ." On behalf of
                     himself and his brothers, declining the position of Chair of Agriculture;
                     commenting on his geological research. 2 pp.

ALS, Oyster Bay, NY. Thanking her for a book and letters; commenting on
                           his growing ability to assess men based on facts and less on opinions;
                           declining to write a biography of Jefferson. 4 pp.

ALS, Middletown, CT. Thanking his father for providing him with a solid
                           foundation of love, principle, and the capacity for first-hand thought;
                           with family news. 4 pp.
